
To allow ssh signing:

$ gh api users/wrp/keys --jq '.[] | "${USER?}@github.com " + .key' >> ~/.ssh/allowed_signers
$ git config --global gpg.ssh.allowedSignersFile ~/.ssh/allowed_signers

In the logformat:
'%G?'::
	"B" for a bad signature,
	"E" if the signature cannot be checked (e.g. missing key)
	"G" for a good (valid) signature,
	"N" for no signature
	"R" for a good signature made by a revoked key,
	"U" for a good signature with unknown validity,
	"X" for a good signature that has expired,
	"Y" for a good signature made by an expired key,


To verify keys as trusted, fetch and sign the GPG key:

	key_id=$(git verify-commit $oid | sed -n '$p')  # 40 hex digits
	gpg --keyserver keyserver.ubuntu.com --recv-keys $key_id
	gpg --lsign-key $key_id

--recv-keys imports the public key from a keyserver.
--lsign-key locally signs it, which marks it as trusted on your machine without publishing that trust to any keyserver.
